{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509376"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11423"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11423"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.59,0.28,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34246"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4058"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19420"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43867"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/34246"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a three day history of yellowing of the skin and confusion. He has mild abdominal pain in the right upper quadrant and anorexia. On examination, there is severe jaundice of the sclera and the skin. His medical history is unremarkable and he does not use any medications. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks four glasses of wine a day. On examination the patient is agitated and disoriented to time and place. His blood pressure is 138/90 mmHg, pulse 98/min and temperature 38.4C. The liver is palpable and tender upon palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial investigations show a macrocytic anaemia with mild thrombocytopenia. His liver function tests are as follows (image):\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choledocholithiasis","Alcoholic hepatitis","Cholangitis","Acute viral hepatitis","Acute cholecystitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcoholic hepatitis \u003C/strong\u003E, an acute inflammation of the liver. Many of these patients - but not all - will have an underlying cirrhosis due to chronic excessive alcohol consumption. Several factors contribute in the pathogenesis of the disease including genetic factors and gut-derived microbial components. Alcoholic hepatitis commonly present with upper abdominal pain, jaundice, fever, and mental alteration. Signs of mental alteration should raise suspicion of withdrawal symptoms and wernicke encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERoutine investigations for patients with suspected alcoholic hepatitis include CBE, LFT, viral hepatitis serology, and coagulation studies. Thiamine level can also be done. In this patient, investigation findings of macrocytic anaemia with mild thrombocytopenia further support the diagnosis of alcoholic hepatitis. Typical liver function test (LFT) findings of alcoholic hepatitis are an AST:ALT ratio of about 2:1, a highly elevated GGT and slightly elevated bilirubin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPut together, the clinical presentation, the history of alcohol consumption and the liver function test results, are sufficient to make the diagnosis of alcoholic hepatitis. If diagnosis of alcoholic hepatitis is unclear, the gold-standard investigation is a liver biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the clinical picture of abdominal pain, fever and jaundice could fit for\u003Cstrong\u003E choledocholithiasis \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Echolangitis, \u003C/strong\u003Ethe AST and ALT would only be marginally elevated, whereas they are considerably raised in this case. The GGT can be elevated in both liver parenchymal disease and bile duct damage or obstruction. The liver function test results in patients with biliary obstruction typically present with raised ALP that is \u0026gt;200 IU/L, and 3x more than ALT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute viral hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely diagnosis. The LFT results of an acute viral hepatitis typically show a markedly increase AST and ALT, making alcoholic hepatitis a more likely diagnosis. However viral hepatitis is an important differential diagnosis in this case, and hepatitis serology should be ordered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis \u003C/strong\u003Edoes not commonly present with jaundice. Similar to choledocholithiasis and cholangitis, LFT results typically present with highly elevated ALP that is \u0026gt;200 IU/L.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Typical LFT findings of alcoholic hepatitis are an AST:ALT ratio of about 2:1, a highly elevated GGT and slightly elevated bilirubin."],"references":["Hosseini N, Shor J, Szabo G. Alcoholic hepatitis: a review. Alcohol and Alcoholism. 2019 Jul 1;54(4):408-16.Viewed July 2022. Available via: https://academic.oup.com/alcalc/article/54/4/408/5521010?login=true","Torruellas C, French SW, Medici V. Diagnosis of alcoholic liver disease. World Journal of Gastroenterology: WJG. 2014 Sep 9;20(33):11684. Viewed July 2022. Available via: Diagnosis of alcoholic liver disease","Coates P. Liver function Test. Australian Family Physician. 2011 Mach; Vol.40; No. 3.  Viewed July 2022. Available via: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/36d1c5e0-9c1d-43fc-a8a0-b323e3ed8fbe/Liver-function-tests.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11423"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19685"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19685"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b1dbcd19-9b87-4e0a-8ccd-d7bcc0f8a8a4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b1dbcd19-9b87-4e0a-8ccd-d7bcc0f8a8a4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":734,"height":456}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/19420"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-04-01T10:12:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-04-01T10:12:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4058"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34246"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","p